How It Works
A lecture is created from YouTube or upload in lectures.py (line 299).
The background job starts from lecture_service.py (line 127).
The pipeline prepares media, downloads YouTube audio, or uses uploaded media in pipeline.py (line 159).
If YouTube captions exist, it uses those as the transcript. If not, it extracts/splits audio and sends chunks for transcription.
Transcription uses Google Gemini in transcription_service.py (line 124).
The cleaned transcript is passed into notes_svc.generate_somali_notes(cleaned_text) at pipeline.py (line 472).
Transcript and notes are saved only near the end at pipeline.py (line 523) and pipeline.py (line 539).
Models
This app is using Google GenAI/Gemini API, not OpenAI.
Configured in backend/app/core/config.py (line 14):
Transcription: gemini-2.5-flash-lite
Chatbot fallback/model: gemini-2.5-flash
Somali notes primary model: gemma-4-31b-it
Notes fallback model: gemini-2.5-flash
So Somali notes first try GEMMA_MODEL, then fallback to GEMINI_CHAT_MODEL, both through the Google google-genai client.
Why You See Empty Notes
Your screenshot says processing was canceled. When that happens, the app does not save notes. The frontend then shows fallback text from page.tsx (line 1186):
Somali notes are not ready yet.
Key points are not available yet.
No generated notes available yet.
So for that lecture, press Reprocess Lecture and let it finish until status is completed.
For improving quality, the main issue is also clear: the backend schema only asks for three outputs: summary, key_points, and structured_content. For a 122-minute video, we should upgrade the prompt/validation to require much richer structured_content, more headings, more key points, glossary, examples, revision questions, and chunk-by-chunk detailed sections. That improvement belongs mainly in note_generation_service.py.